57
00:02:43,400 --> 00:02:45,240
Welcome Robin.

58
00:02:45,240 --> 00:02:46,600
Good to be with you.

59
00:02:46,600 --> 00:02:48,040
It's a pleasure.

60
00:02:48,040 --> 00:02:51,000
We will hopefully get into quite some detail

61
00:02:51,000 --> 00:02:52,280
about Perikan today,

62
00:02:52,280 --> 00:02:55,640
but let's start with an overview and broad definition.

63
00:02:55,640 --> 00:02:57,080
What is Perikan?

64
00:02:58,040 --> 00:03:03,040
It's an attempt to say something concrete

65
00:03:03,040 --> 00:03:07,040
about what it is that we think that socialists

66
00:03:08,440 --> 00:03:11,640
should be proposing as the kind of economic system

67
00:03:12,960 --> 00:03:16,720
that we wanna replace capitalism with in the 21st century.

68
00:03:17,720 --> 00:03:21,920
In the light of all of the experiences

69
00:03:21,920 --> 00:03:25,720
with different attempts to create a socialist economy

70
00:03:25,720 --> 00:03:28,480
in the 20th century, what lessons have we learned

71
00:03:28,480 --> 00:03:32,320
and what should we now be proposing?

72
00:03:32,320 --> 00:03:34,960
It's our proposal of what we left us

73
00:03:34,960 --> 00:03:36,600
who wanna replace capitalism

74
00:03:36,600 --> 00:03:38,360
with a far better economic system,

75
00:03:38,360 --> 00:03:42,440
a kind of socialism that's very democratic

76
00:03:42,440 --> 00:03:45,240
and that encourages popular participation.

77
00:03:47,720 --> 00:03:52,480
And the other thing is that we thought that for too long,

78
00:03:52,480 --> 00:03:56,920
anti-capitalists have just been very vague

79
00:03:56,920 --> 00:04:01,920
about what it is they want in light of the Soviet experience

80
00:04:02,320 --> 00:04:04,800
in the Eastern European countries and Cuba.

81
00:04:06,480 --> 00:04:11,320
In light of all that, we felt like reasonable people

82
00:04:11,320 --> 00:04:14,160
would expect, you have to say something

83
00:04:14,200 --> 00:04:17,440
a little more concrete than just your values

84
00:04:17,440 --> 00:04:20,400
and your wishes for how the economy should work.

85
00:04:21,520 --> 00:04:24,000
So we thought, well, let's begin that process

86
00:04:24,000 --> 00:04:27,240
by making some very, very concrete proposals

87
00:04:27,240 --> 00:04:29,240
about how all the different kinds of decisions

88
00:04:29,240 --> 00:04:31,680
that have to be made, how they might best be made,

89
00:04:31,680 --> 00:04:33,480
and then we can all talk about it.

90
00:04:33,480 --> 00:04:37,040
So that was the motivation, that was the purpose

91
00:04:37,040 --> 00:04:39,040
for putting something out there.

92
00:04:39,040 --> 00:04:41,400
And then we had to discuss what label to put on it,

93
00:04:41,400 --> 00:04:43,000
and we ended up with, well, let's call it

94
00:04:43,040 --> 00:04:45,520
a participatory economy.

95
00:04:45,520 --> 00:04:47,420
So that was the origins.

96
00:04:48,640 --> 00:04:52,000
Michael and I were very much together on that wavelength

97
00:04:52,000 --> 00:04:57,000
and the first books we published about it were back in 1990.

98
00:04:57,640 --> 00:05:00,120
So at this point, it's been around a while.

99
00:05:02,640 --> 00:05:05,360
And after the fall of the wall

100
00:05:06,600 --> 00:05:09,720
and the sort of crumbling of the centrally planned economies

101
00:05:09,720 --> 00:05:11,840
in the Soviet Union and Eastern Europe,

102
00:05:11,840 --> 00:05:16,000
there's now been a 30-year debate

103
00:05:16,000 --> 00:05:18,440
about what should socialists be championing.

104
00:05:18,440 --> 00:05:21,460
And there's various schools of thought.

105
00:05:21,460 --> 00:05:24,580
There's a lot of proposals about market socialism.

106
00:05:25,680 --> 00:05:28,840
There's basically proposals about taking

107
00:05:28,840 --> 00:05:32,540
social democratic capitalism as far as you can take it.

108
00:05:32,540 --> 00:05:34,180
I would call that's Alec Nove.

109
00:05:35,660 --> 00:05:38,320
And then there are other people who have continued to say,

110
00:05:38,320 --> 00:05:40,560
no, we want a lot more planning than that.

111
00:05:40,560 --> 00:05:44,560
Market socialism isn't really what we socialists

112
00:05:44,560 --> 00:05:46,360
should be championing in the future.

113
00:05:47,200 --> 00:05:49,480
We really need to talk seriously about planning

114
00:05:49,480 --> 00:05:51,560
and different forms of planning.

115
00:05:51,560 --> 00:05:56,560
So this proposal is one of the proposals that's out there

116
00:05:56,920 --> 00:06:00,920
that sort of fits into that 30-year debate.

117
00:06:00,920 --> 00:06:03,800
And in that context, it's been argued about

118
00:06:03,800 --> 00:06:06,120
in various journals and at various conferences

119
00:06:06,120 --> 00:06:08,100
over the past 30 years.

120
00:06:08,100 --> 00:06:12,060
And there are some basic principles that inform pericon.

121
00:06:12,060 --> 00:06:14,620
And these are in short, self-governance

122
00:06:14,620 --> 00:06:17,700
through democratic councils of workers and consumers

123
00:06:17,700 --> 00:06:19,460
and their respective federations.

124
00:06:19,460 --> 00:06:20,620
That's the first one.

125
00:06:20,620 --> 00:06:23,780
The second one would be jobs balanced for empowerment,

126
00:06:23,780 --> 00:06:26,460
desirability and caring labor.

127
00:06:26,460 --> 00:06:30,260
The third one would be remuneration according to sacrifice

128
00:06:30,260 --> 00:06:32,660
or effort as judged by coworkers.

129
00:06:32,660 --> 00:06:35,980
And the fourth one would be economic coordination

130
00:06:35,980 --> 00:06:38,980
through a participatory planning procedure.

131
00:06:38,980 --> 00:06:41,860
I would very much like to go through all of them.

132
00:06:41,860 --> 00:06:44,180
Let's start with self-governance.

133
00:06:44,180 --> 00:06:46,700
How would democratic self-governance

134
00:06:46,700 --> 00:06:48,740
be achieved in pericon?

135
00:06:48,740 --> 00:06:50,740
You did a brilliant job of summarizing

136
00:06:50,740 --> 00:06:52,400
the major features of the proposal,

137
00:06:52,400 --> 00:06:54,500
so I don't have to, thank you.

138
00:06:54,500 --> 00:06:59,500
First, we've argued that it's very clear

139
00:06:59,940 --> 00:07:03,660
that it's very important to think very hard

140
00:07:03,660 --> 00:07:07,040
about exactly what you think economic democracy means.

141
00:07:09,180 --> 00:07:12,140
And there's two different views

142
00:07:12,140 --> 00:07:15,260
about what economic democracy means

143
00:07:15,260 --> 00:07:16,900
that are really dominant.

144
00:07:16,900 --> 00:07:20,140
One is, well, it's like politics.

145
00:07:20,140 --> 00:07:24,160
I mean, democratic politics is everybody gets a vote.

146
00:07:24,160 --> 00:07:27,500
Everybody gets a vote and everybody gets the same vote.

147
00:07:27,500 --> 00:07:29,200
How else can you do this?

148
00:07:29,200 --> 00:07:32,220
In economics, there's also this concept

149
00:07:32,220 --> 00:07:33,780
that's been around for a long time

150
00:07:33,780 --> 00:07:36,580
that right-wingers like Milton Friedman

151
00:07:36,580 --> 00:07:38,060
called economic freedom.

152
00:07:39,520 --> 00:07:42,420
And that is, well, I should be free to do

153
00:07:42,420 --> 00:07:46,100
with my person and property whatever I want.

154
00:07:46,100 --> 00:07:48,760
And we want a system that allows people to do that.

155
00:07:49,780 --> 00:07:54,180
And so we have begun, we try to begin the discussion

156
00:07:54,180 --> 00:07:57,420
by pointing out that both of these approaches

157
00:07:57,420 --> 00:08:01,940
to what economic democracy or economic freedom means,

158
00:08:01,940 --> 00:08:06,180
they don't apply in most situations

159
00:08:07,340 --> 00:08:11,180
because particularly when economic decisions are made,

160
00:08:11,180 --> 00:08:15,480
what will happen is any economic decision you look at

161
00:08:15,480 --> 00:08:17,820
will affect some people more than other people.

162
00:08:19,120 --> 00:08:22,380
So one person, one vote works

163
00:08:22,380 --> 00:08:25,940
as a notion of economic democracy in those cases

164
00:08:25,940 --> 00:08:28,320
where everybody is affected more or less equally

165
00:08:28,320 --> 00:08:29,260
by the decision.

166
00:08:30,260 --> 00:08:34,020
And economic freedom works for decisions

167
00:08:34,020 --> 00:08:35,420
that really only affect me.

168
00:08:35,420 --> 00:08:38,900
I mean, what color underwear should I put on today?

169
00:08:38,900 --> 00:08:41,700
So yeah, of course, we want economic freedom

170
00:08:41,700 --> 00:08:43,440
is the right way to make that decision.

171
00:08:43,440 --> 00:08:45,880
I get to decide, nobody gets to tell me that.

172
00:08:48,100 --> 00:08:52,020
On the other hand, most economic decisions

173
00:08:52,020 --> 00:08:54,940
are decisions where some people will be affected,

174
00:08:55,900 --> 00:08:58,140
more than one person will be affected,

175
00:08:58,140 --> 00:09:00,860
but some people will be affected more than others.

176
00:09:00,860 --> 00:09:02,980
So we have begun by saying,

177
00:09:02,980 --> 00:09:05,800
let's be clear what the goal is here.

178
00:09:05,800 --> 00:09:09,280
The goal is we want to design procedures

179
00:09:09,280 --> 00:09:10,860
for making economic decisions

180
00:09:10,860 --> 00:09:14,340
so that people would approximately have influence

181
00:09:14,340 --> 00:09:17,900
over a decision to the degree that they are affected.

182
00:09:19,260 --> 00:09:23,780
And that's sort of, that's our starting point

183
00:09:23,780 --> 00:09:26,340
in terms of how we go about thinking

184
00:09:26,340 --> 00:09:28,780
about what a democratic economy means.

185
00:09:28,780 --> 00:09:30,980
And we call that self-management.

186
00:09:30,980 --> 00:09:33,900
We define self-management as decision-making input

187
00:09:33,900 --> 00:09:36,660
over things to the degree that you're affected.

188
00:09:36,660 --> 00:09:38,580
And in some cases, that means I'll have more

189
00:09:38,580 --> 00:09:40,500
decision-making authority or input

190
00:09:40,500 --> 00:09:41,980
than somebody else does.

191
00:09:41,980 --> 00:09:44,860
And in some cases, it'll mean I have some input,

192
00:09:44,860 --> 00:09:47,500
but I don't have as much input as other people.

193
00:09:47,500 --> 00:09:50,720
And in the particular context of workplaces,

194
00:09:50,720 --> 00:09:55,660
what a workplace produces and what technologies they use

195
00:09:55,700 --> 00:09:59,260
and how they go about organizing their work process,

196
00:09:59,260 --> 00:10:01,560
clearly those decisions affect people

197
00:10:01,560 --> 00:10:04,920
in what we propose to be a worker's council,

198
00:10:06,540 --> 00:10:09,520
far more than they affect all sorts of other people.

199
00:10:09,520 --> 00:10:10,980
But it's not that,

200
00:10:10,980 --> 00:10:14,540
their decisions clearly affect other people as well.

201
00:10:14,540 --> 00:10:18,300
What they decide to produce is going to affect consumers.

202
00:10:18,300 --> 00:10:22,060
And if they use these inputs rather than those inputs,

203
00:10:22,060 --> 00:10:27,060
it means, well, if they use particular parts of land,

204
00:10:29,300 --> 00:10:31,020
if they use a piece of land,

205
00:10:31,020 --> 00:10:33,660
that means somebody else can't use it.

206
00:10:33,660 --> 00:10:34,940
So we start with that.

207
00:10:34,940 --> 00:10:36,680
We start with that.

208
00:10:36,680 --> 00:10:40,620
You mentioned that we also start with sort of a position

209
00:10:40,620 --> 00:10:43,380
about, well, what would be a fair way

210
00:10:43,380 --> 00:10:47,180
to distribute the burdens and benefits of economic activity?

211
00:10:47,180 --> 00:10:50,760
And this is something that's hotly contested

212
00:10:50,760 --> 00:10:53,560
by socialists and has been for,

213
00:10:53,560 --> 00:10:55,560
since socialism first became

214
00:10:55,560 --> 00:10:58,480
some sort of an ideology in a movement.

215
00:10:58,480 --> 00:11:02,320
What is a fair, just how should workers be rewarded?

216
00:11:02,320 --> 00:11:05,260
On what basis should people be rewarded?

217
00:11:05,260 --> 00:11:09,020
And we've argued that when you go through all of that,

218
00:11:09,020 --> 00:11:10,960
and you think it through clearly,

219
00:11:10,960 --> 00:11:13,760
that a desirable economy would be one

220
00:11:13,760 --> 00:11:16,760
in which workers are rewarded according

221
00:11:16,760 --> 00:11:19,260
to the sacrifices they make when they work.

222
00:11:20,180 --> 00:11:21,760
We've also used the word effort.

223
00:11:21,760 --> 00:11:23,980
Sometimes some people, I mean,

224
00:11:23,980 --> 00:11:26,780
I know there are times when I'm working harder.

225
00:11:26,780 --> 00:11:30,100
I know when there are times when I'm working less hard.

226
00:11:30,100 --> 00:11:32,500
And those who work harder

227
00:11:32,500 --> 00:11:34,740
probably deserve more compensation.

228
00:11:36,300 --> 00:11:38,340
And certainly people who work,

229
00:11:38,340 --> 00:11:40,420
who make greater sacrifices than they work.

230
00:11:40,420 --> 00:11:42,540
I mean, neoclassical economists

231
00:11:42,540 --> 00:11:44,380
call it the disutility of labor.

232
00:11:45,420 --> 00:11:47,420
You're working right now,

233
00:11:47,420 --> 00:11:49,500
but your disutility isn't very high.

234
00:11:49,500 --> 00:11:52,140
You're doing something that you find more,

235
00:11:52,140 --> 00:11:54,100
you're doing something you find more or less pleasant.

236
00:11:54,100 --> 00:11:57,680
The coal miner who goes down a shaft

237
00:11:57,680 --> 00:12:01,300
and exposes themselves to coal dust

238
00:12:01,300 --> 00:12:05,860
and is sweating and coming home sore at the end of the day

239
00:12:05,860 --> 00:12:09,900
is making more sacrifices than somebody who,

240
00:12:09,900 --> 00:12:11,420
somebody like you or me is

241
00:12:11,420 --> 00:12:13,840
during most of the time when we're working.

242
00:12:13,840 --> 00:12:16,860
So we just think those things should be taken into account.

243
00:12:16,900 --> 00:12:18,340
Those are legitimate reasons

244
00:12:18,340 --> 00:12:22,140
for why some people should sometimes be compensated

245
00:12:22,140 --> 00:12:23,420
by more than others.

246
00:12:23,420 --> 00:12:27,060
Now, how you go about doing that.

247
00:12:27,060 --> 00:12:29,900
So how you go about arranging for economic decisions

248
00:12:29,900 --> 00:12:31,940
to be made according to this principle

249
00:12:31,940 --> 00:12:35,660
or goal of self-management

250
00:12:35,660 --> 00:12:39,340
and how it is that you arrange for people to be compensated

251
00:12:39,340 --> 00:12:40,820
according to their sacrifice.

252
00:12:40,820 --> 00:12:43,180
Well, but at least we understand

253
00:12:43,180 --> 00:12:45,540
what we're trying to accomplish.

254
00:12:45,700 --> 00:12:48,460
And we were very self-conscious from the very beginning

255
00:12:48,460 --> 00:12:50,820
and coming up with proposals

256
00:12:50,820 --> 00:12:53,520
for how you would actually achieve those goals.

257
00:12:54,460 --> 00:12:56,500
Now, one thing I'll be very honest about,

258
00:12:56,500 --> 00:12:59,780
we did not think about very much back in 1990

259
00:12:59,780 --> 00:13:01,820
was environmental sustainability.

260
00:13:03,860 --> 00:13:05,860
So I will plead guilty

261
00:13:05,860 --> 00:13:08,940
as long as most of my socialist comrades of my age

262
00:13:08,940 --> 00:13:11,460
are willing to plead guilty along with me

263
00:13:11,460 --> 00:13:14,620
because we really should.

264
00:13:16,540 --> 00:13:19,940
Leftists and socialists, I believe,

265
00:13:19,940 --> 00:13:24,300
where Johnny come lately to environmental awareness.

266
00:13:24,300 --> 00:13:25,740
We were just so concerned

267
00:13:25,740 --> 00:13:27,540
with all sorts of other things we cared about.

268
00:13:27,540 --> 00:13:31,360
Oh, economic self-management and economic justice

269
00:13:31,360 --> 00:13:35,220
that we sort of took environmental things for granted.

270
00:13:35,220 --> 00:13:38,320
And in many ways, we're just like everybody else

271
00:13:38,320 --> 00:13:40,700
in terms of being woefully un-woke

272
00:13:40,700 --> 00:13:43,700
on the subject of what was happening with the environment.

273
00:13:43,700 --> 00:13:47,700
But one of the things I'm really proud of is,

274
00:13:47,700 --> 00:13:52,300
and this was, I will give my wife credit for this.

275
00:13:53,300 --> 00:13:56,460
My wife is an environmental economist

276
00:13:56,460 --> 00:14:00,320
and she brought her leftist husband

277
00:14:00,320 --> 00:14:04,040
to awareness about just how negligent

278
00:14:04,040 --> 00:14:05,820
me and my fellow comrades were

279
00:14:05,820 --> 00:14:08,440
in our thinking about environmental issues.

280
00:14:08,440 --> 00:14:12,580
And now I have become, as a professional economist,

281
00:14:12,580 --> 00:14:15,260
I teach political economy, I teach economic theory,

282
00:14:15,260 --> 00:14:16,900
but for more than 20 years,

283
00:14:16,900 --> 00:14:19,760
I've also taught environmental economics.

284
00:14:19,760 --> 00:14:23,700
I can almost prove my point about negligence on the left.

285
00:14:23,700 --> 00:14:25,780
So I taught in an economics department

286
00:14:25,780 --> 00:14:27,460
at American University,

287
00:14:27,460 --> 00:14:31,740
known as sort of a heterodox school of economics,

288
00:14:31,740 --> 00:14:34,580
a PhD program that studied political economy

289
00:14:34,580 --> 00:14:39,000
as well as mainstream economics.

290
00:14:39,000 --> 00:14:41,840
We didn't have a professor, you know,

291
00:14:41,840 --> 00:14:44,680
who was a specialist in environmental economics

292
00:14:44,680 --> 00:14:48,060
for the first 15 years I taught in that program.

293
00:14:49,160 --> 00:14:52,240
And I became an environmental economist

294
00:14:52,240 --> 00:14:53,920
because somebody had raised their hand

295
00:14:53,920 --> 00:14:54,920
and said, who's gonna teach

296
00:14:54,920 --> 00:14:56,560
the environmental economics class?

297
00:14:56,560 --> 00:14:58,920
And I said, you know, okay, so I'll do that.

298
00:14:58,920 --> 00:15:00,760
So that's how I became somebody

299
00:15:00,760 --> 00:15:03,740
who actually learned enough about environmental economics

300
00:15:03,740 --> 00:15:08,740
to realize that you have clearly in the year 2020,

301
00:15:09,340 --> 00:15:13,940
clearly any economy to be desirable

302
00:15:13,940 --> 00:15:17,940
has to be an economy that's designed in ways

303
00:15:17,940 --> 00:15:19,860
that is going to help us protect

304
00:15:19,860 --> 00:15:21,900
and preserve the natural environment

305
00:15:23,660 --> 00:15:25,580
far better than any economic system

306
00:15:25,580 --> 00:15:27,540
that people have used up until now.

307
00:15:27,540 --> 00:15:30,820
So I very self-consciously now add the goal

308
00:15:30,820 --> 00:15:33,060
of environmental sustainability, you know,

309
00:15:33,060 --> 00:15:35,660
to economic democracy and economic justice.

310
00:15:36,620 --> 00:15:40,460
And we will get to the mechanisms

311
00:15:40,460 --> 00:15:43,300
that have been incorporated into Perrican

312
00:15:43,300 --> 00:15:45,980
in order to address this question.

313
00:15:45,980 --> 00:15:50,700
Before we go there, maybe you could like guide the audience

314
00:15:50,700 --> 00:15:53,540
through this basic setup of institutions within Perrican.

315
00:15:53,540 --> 00:15:55,740
So this is sort of a thumbnail sketch

316
00:15:55,740 --> 00:15:59,600
of what the major features of a participatory economy are.

317
00:16:01,060 --> 00:16:02,420
We propose that,

318
00:16:03,180 --> 00:16:06,880
that the first is workers councils.

319
00:16:07,820 --> 00:16:10,300
So we don't have private corporations.

320
00:16:12,020 --> 00:16:14,940
Workplaces are governed by a workers council

321
00:16:14,940 --> 00:16:16,540
where every worker has one vote.

322
00:16:16,540 --> 00:16:20,400
And we can go back to our suggestions or proposals

323
00:16:20,400 --> 00:16:23,320
for how it is that workers councils might want to proceed

324
00:16:23,320 --> 00:16:26,640
in their own process of self-governance.

325
00:16:26,640 --> 00:16:28,960
But we have workers councils.

326
00:16:28,960 --> 00:16:32,020
We also have proposed that consumers,

327
00:16:32,820 --> 00:16:34,540
that consumers be organized

328
00:16:34,540 --> 00:16:37,220
into what we call neighborhood consumer councils.

329
00:16:38,160 --> 00:16:42,620
Because we want to enfranchise consumers

330
00:16:42,620 --> 00:16:45,060
in our planning processes.

331
00:16:45,060 --> 00:16:46,780
And if they act as individuals,

332
00:16:46,780 --> 00:16:50,020
it's very difficult for us to incorporate them

333
00:16:50,020 --> 00:16:51,340
into planning procedures.

334
00:16:51,340 --> 00:16:53,780
But if we simply say

335
00:16:53,780 --> 00:16:58,020
that we organize neighborhood consumption councils

336
00:16:58,020 --> 00:17:00,620
where we're talking about maybe 5,000

337
00:17:00,620 --> 00:17:03,740
or 6,000 families that are living in a neighborhood.

338
00:17:03,740 --> 00:17:07,000
So these are geographically defined neighborhoods.

339
00:17:07,000 --> 00:17:09,940
And we just want the size of the council to be such

340
00:17:09,940 --> 00:17:13,020
that you could reasonably participate

341
00:17:13,020 --> 00:17:15,940
by going to meetings in your neighborhood

342
00:17:15,940 --> 00:17:17,460
consumption council.

343
00:17:17,460 --> 00:17:21,100
So that's another sort of major institutional proposal

344
00:17:21,100 --> 00:17:22,500
that we have.

345
00:17:22,500 --> 00:17:24,500
It's a way, we think it's important

346
00:17:24,500 --> 00:17:28,580
to enfranchise consumers in planning procedures

347
00:17:28,620 --> 00:17:31,420
along with workers in their workplace.

348
00:17:31,420 --> 00:17:34,700
What's probably most innovative about our proposal,

349
00:17:34,700 --> 00:17:39,260
I believe, is that there's two different ways

350
00:17:39,260 --> 00:17:43,180
that people have thought you could integrate

351
00:17:43,180 --> 00:17:44,820
the interrelated activities

352
00:17:44,820 --> 00:17:47,360
of hundreds of thousands of workers councils

353
00:17:47,360 --> 00:17:49,980
and hundreds of thousands of consumer councils.

354
00:17:49,980 --> 00:17:52,180
And one would be simply through the market.

355
00:17:53,500 --> 00:17:56,760
Because consumers have to buy what workers,

356
00:17:56,760 --> 00:18:00,360
consumers have to get what workers councils are producing

357
00:18:00,360 --> 00:18:04,360
and different workers councils have to receive inputs.

358
00:18:04,360 --> 00:18:07,440
So there is a, you have to coordinate all this.

359
00:18:08,420 --> 00:18:12,240
And the two ways that the dominant thinking

360
00:18:12,240 --> 00:18:14,620
about how to coordinate all this is,

361
00:18:14,620 --> 00:18:16,440
well, you either have to coordinate it

362
00:18:16,440 --> 00:18:18,640
through market exchanges,

363
00:18:18,640 --> 00:18:22,460
or you're gonna need some sort of central agency

364
00:18:22,460 --> 00:18:24,640
that gathers all the information

365
00:18:25,600 --> 00:18:28,000
and then puts together a coherent plan

366
00:18:28,000 --> 00:18:29,600
for how all this could work out.

367
00:18:30,680 --> 00:18:35,680
And what we have said is both of those are a disaster

368
00:18:35,880 --> 00:18:40,880
that we now can foreseeably predict sort of some,

369
00:18:42,920 --> 00:18:47,920
at least with the, I mean, hindsight's perfect,

370
00:18:47,980 --> 00:18:52,000
but we have the 20th century of hindsight

371
00:18:52,000 --> 00:18:54,720
to see what happened when socialists tried

372
00:18:54,720 --> 00:18:58,960
to somehow have a central planning agency,

373
00:18:58,960 --> 00:19:01,640
be in charge of this coordinating process.

374
00:19:01,640 --> 00:19:03,560
And it's not a good outcome.

375
00:19:03,560 --> 00:19:06,260
And then the question is, but is there an alternative?

376
00:19:07,220 --> 00:19:11,360
And our answer was, there is an alternative.

377
00:19:11,360 --> 00:19:15,180
And what's I think particularly interesting about it is,

378
00:19:15,180 --> 00:19:20,080
I think the alternative is exactly what early socialists

379
00:19:20,120 --> 00:19:23,160
always thought would go on if you go back

380
00:19:23,160 --> 00:19:26,520
to the late 1900s and early 20th century.

381
00:19:26,520 --> 00:19:30,000
What they always thought was, well, these workers councils,

382
00:19:30,000 --> 00:19:33,720
of course they have, their activities are interrelated.

383
00:19:33,720 --> 00:19:36,840
They're gonna have to plan together

384
00:19:36,840 --> 00:19:38,700
how that interrelation works out.

385
00:19:39,720 --> 00:19:44,720
And so we very self-consciously tried to design procedures

386
00:19:46,600 --> 00:19:49,600
that would essentially take that view

387
00:19:49,600 --> 00:19:51,440
of what it is we're attempting to do.

388
00:19:52,480 --> 00:19:55,880
Is there some way that we could have workers councils

389
00:19:55,880 --> 00:19:58,000
proposing what they wanna do,

390
00:19:58,000 --> 00:20:01,760
consumer councils saying, this is what we wanna consume?

391
00:20:01,760 --> 00:20:04,640
And is there some way that they could make

392
00:20:04,640 --> 00:20:08,160
what I call sort of self-activity proposals

393
00:20:08,160 --> 00:20:13,160
and then discover what the consequences of that are,

394
00:20:13,300 --> 00:20:16,600
and then go back to the drawing board

395
00:20:16,600 --> 00:20:20,440
and revise the proposals and resubmit them

396
00:20:20,440 --> 00:20:24,520
so that we could find a feasible plan in this way.

397
00:20:24,520 --> 00:20:26,800
And we wouldn't have a central planning agency

398
00:20:26,800 --> 00:20:28,440
sitting on top of everybody saying,

399
00:20:28,440 --> 00:20:30,080
well, what you propose doesn't work,

400
00:20:30,080 --> 00:20:31,620
you're gonna have to do this.

401
00:20:32,720 --> 00:20:37,720
And we wouldn't have market forces driving the outcome.

402
00:20:40,920 --> 00:20:41,960
Is there really any reason

403
00:20:41,960 --> 00:20:44,360
that we couldn't do things that way?

404
00:20:44,360 --> 00:20:47,620
So we've worked on it sort of theoretically,

405
00:20:49,160 --> 00:20:52,200
and now we've worked on it with sort of computer simulations

406
00:20:52,200 --> 00:20:54,640
to see whether something that we can prove

407
00:20:54,640 --> 00:20:57,300
under certain assumptions would reach a feasible

408
00:20:57,300 --> 00:21:00,260
and desirable and efficient plan under.

409
00:21:01,440 --> 00:21:03,200
This is what economists do.

410
00:21:03,200 --> 00:21:06,080
We say, well, if you make certain assumptions

411
00:21:06,080 --> 00:21:07,760
about preferences people have,

412
00:21:07,760 --> 00:21:10,360
if you make certain assumptions about technologies

413
00:21:10,600 --> 00:21:15,000
that producers have, then under those assumptions,

414
00:21:15,000 --> 00:21:16,640
you can prove that some procedure

415
00:21:16,640 --> 00:21:19,160
will reach a particular outcome.

416
00:21:19,160 --> 00:21:23,600
And way back in 1990, we essentially said

417
00:21:23,600 --> 00:21:26,440
under far less rigorous assumptions

418
00:21:26,440 --> 00:21:29,800
than you need to prove that a market capitalist economy

419
00:21:29,800 --> 00:21:32,120
will reach an efficient outcome.

420
00:21:32,120 --> 00:21:33,960
We can say this process,

421
00:21:33,960 --> 00:21:36,520
which we think was what early socialists

422
00:21:36,680 --> 00:21:40,760
and most people drawn to socialism always wanted instead.

423
00:21:40,760 --> 00:21:42,640
This process will work out.

424
00:21:42,640 --> 00:21:44,840
This process could, it works in theory.

425
00:21:46,980 --> 00:21:51,460
Now that left the issue of, but is it practical?

426
00:21:52,400 --> 00:21:53,600
And we'll come back to this,

427
00:21:53,600 --> 00:21:56,780
but I mean here to put the issue very, very bluntly.

428
00:21:57,760 --> 00:22:00,960
Well, in theory, if we still have,

429
00:22:00,960 --> 00:22:03,680
if we allow the workers and the consumer neighborhood

430
00:22:03,680 --> 00:22:06,060
consumer councils to keep making proposals

431
00:22:06,620 --> 00:22:09,380
and revising their proposals enough times,

432
00:22:09,380 --> 00:22:11,540
in theory, we'll come to a feasible plan

433
00:22:11,540 --> 00:22:13,100
that we can start the year with.

434
00:22:14,380 --> 00:22:18,180
But what if it takes 1000 revisions?

435
00:22:18,180 --> 00:22:20,560
Well, then it becomes a practical impossibility.

436
00:22:20,560 --> 00:22:23,700
So that question was left aside until,

437
00:22:23,700 --> 00:22:25,060
I mean, the best way to answer it

438
00:22:25,060 --> 00:22:27,960
is to convince some country they wanna try it.

439
00:22:27,960 --> 00:22:30,860
But until that happens, then the only answer is

440
00:22:30,860 --> 00:22:32,960
you try and do some computer simulations

441
00:22:32,960 --> 00:22:33,900
to see what happens.

442
00:22:33,900 --> 00:22:35,580
And we now basically have done that

443
00:22:36,100 --> 00:22:39,020
and we have some, I think some pretty interesting,

444
00:22:39,020 --> 00:22:41,460
at least preliminary reporting

445
00:22:41,460 --> 00:22:43,260
that we can do on that subject.

446
00:22:43,260 --> 00:22:46,300
Besides the workers councils that are self-managed,

447
00:22:46,300 --> 00:22:49,500
the consumer councils that are also sort of self-governing

448
00:22:49,500 --> 00:22:51,880
and participate in the planning procedure,

449
00:22:52,860 --> 00:22:55,220
our specific proposal for how it is

450
00:22:55,220 --> 00:22:59,180
that annual participatory planning can substitute

451
00:22:59,180 --> 00:23:02,700
for a central planning board and markets

452
00:23:02,700 --> 00:23:04,140
as a way to come up with a plan.

453
00:23:04,140 --> 00:23:09,140
I think that's the sort of unique and it is unique.

454
00:23:10,260 --> 00:23:12,100
And I think it's a very central part

455
00:23:12,100 --> 00:23:13,780
of what our overall proposal is.

456
00:23:15,060 --> 00:23:18,540
And maybe just for the audience

457
00:23:18,540 --> 00:23:21,060
in order to give some orientation,

458
00:23:21,060 --> 00:23:24,620
the mechanism that is an essential part

459
00:23:24,620 --> 00:23:27,860
of this participatory planning procedure

460
00:23:27,860 --> 00:23:30,900
that will take up all of this information

461
00:23:30,900 --> 00:23:34,460
and process it in a way in order to provide

462
00:23:34,460 --> 00:23:38,100
some first estimates on how to proceed.

463
00:23:38,100 --> 00:23:41,500
This institution is called the IFB,

464
00:23:41,500 --> 00:23:45,860
the Iteration Facilitation Board, isn't it?

465
00:23:45,860 --> 00:23:50,540
Yes, you know, when you're creating things

466
00:23:50,540 --> 00:23:52,300
and you have to put names on them,

467
00:23:53,460 --> 00:23:58,460
some choices are felicitous and some are less so.

468
00:23:58,900 --> 00:24:03,580
And Michael Albert and I remember we talked for,

469
00:24:03,580 --> 00:24:05,780
I mean, we had long conversations

470
00:24:05,780 --> 00:24:10,780
about what name do we wanna give to this system or proposal?

471
00:24:11,280 --> 00:24:15,260
And I mean, I remember one of the early ones we thought of

472
00:24:15,260 --> 00:24:17,980
was decentralized socialist planning.

473
00:24:19,920 --> 00:24:24,700
And I'm the economist and Michael's the political activist.

474
00:24:24,700 --> 00:24:26,960
So that appealed to me.

475
00:24:28,820 --> 00:24:30,980
And Michael argued in this time,

476
00:24:30,980 --> 00:24:34,220
I mean, we've had various arguments over the decades

477
00:24:34,220 --> 00:24:35,860
and sometimes I think I've been right

478
00:24:35,860 --> 00:24:37,540
and sometimes I think he was right.

479
00:24:37,540 --> 00:24:39,540
And on this one, he was dead right.

480
00:24:39,540 --> 00:24:41,420
He said, you know what?

481
00:24:41,420 --> 00:24:45,940
I mean, we should call it a participatory economy.

482
00:24:45,940 --> 00:24:48,940
If people wanna call it participatory socialism, that's fine.

483
00:24:48,940 --> 00:24:52,020
If people wanna say, well, how does it fit in

484
00:24:52,020 --> 00:24:54,420
to left ideology?

485
00:24:54,420 --> 00:24:57,940
We can say it's libertarian socialism.

486
00:24:58,820 --> 00:25:02,380
In Europe calling something libertarian socialism,

487
00:25:02,380 --> 00:25:05,060
it works because everybody knows what you mean.

488
00:25:05,060 --> 00:25:08,340
In the United States, that's a huge problem

489
00:25:08,340 --> 00:25:12,580
because the only people who call themselves libertarians

490
00:25:12,580 --> 00:25:15,620
in the United States are right-wing libertarians.

491
00:25:15,620 --> 00:25:18,140
So if you say libertarian socialism,

492
00:25:18,140 --> 00:25:21,900
you mostly just confuse people in the United States.

493
00:25:21,900 --> 00:25:23,380
But in any case, we had to come up

494
00:25:23,420 --> 00:25:25,220
with some sort of a name and he was the one

495
00:25:25,220 --> 00:25:27,020
that was just very insistent.

496
00:25:27,020 --> 00:25:31,700
We really decentralized socialist planning, no, no, no.

497
00:25:31,700 --> 00:25:34,900
We should just call it a participatory economy.

498
00:25:34,900 --> 00:25:36,340
I think he was right about that.

499
00:25:36,340 --> 00:25:38,300
The iteration facilitation board

500
00:25:38,300 --> 00:25:40,120
is a very unfortunate name.

501
00:25:41,380 --> 00:25:43,380
And in anarchist circles,

502
00:25:43,380 --> 00:25:48,380
it's also a very hotly contested issue exactly what it is.

503
00:25:49,220 --> 00:25:53,500
So besides the name being unfortunate, it's clunky.

504
00:25:55,060 --> 00:25:58,460
The real issue is, well, what does it do?

505
00:25:58,460 --> 00:26:01,400
And I'll just go straight to the issue here.

506
00:26:02,820 --> 00:26:06,260
Anarchists are suspicious

507
00:26:07,800 --> 00:26:10,100
that it's just a different name

508
00:26:10,100 --> 00:26:12,500
for the central planning bureau,

509
00:26:12,500 --> 00:26:15,160
that it's a central planning bureau in disguise.

510
00:26:16,000 --> 00:26:20,240
You told us you didn't have a central planning bureau.

511
00:26:20,240 --> 00:26:23,400
You told us that this was an alternative

512
00:26:23,400 --> 00:26:24,880
to central planning,

513
00:26:24,880 --> 00:26:27,020
but you really just sort of hoodwinked us.

514
00:26:27,020 --> 00:26:29,160
You gave it a different name,

515
00:26:29,160 --> 00:26:33,320
but it really is doing what central planning bureaus do.

516
00:26:35,680 --> 00:26:40,160
And so I wanna take care of that immediately.

517
00:26:41,280 --> 00:26:43,120
This thing, whatever you call it,

518
00:26:43,960 --> 00:26:45,360
we haven't got a better name yet,

519
00:26:45,360 --> 00:26:47,220
iteration facilitation board.

520
00:26:47,220 --> 00:26:48,920
This is what it does.

521
00:26:48,920 --> 00:26:52,400
At the beginning of the annual planning process,

522
00:26:52,400 --> 00:26:57,160
it announces whatever the current estimates are

523
00:26:57,160 --> 00:27:00,920
of the opportunity costs of using different resources,

524
00:27:00,920 --> 00:27:04,140
the opportunity cost of using different kinds of labor,

525
00:27:05,120 --> 00:27:07,920
the opportunity cost of using machinery,

526
00:27:07,920 --> 00:27:10,340
stocks of machines that we have,

527
00:27:10,340 --> 00:27:14,580
and whatever estimates the current estimates are

528
00:27:14,580 --> 00:27:17,160
of the social cost of producing different things.

529
00:27:18,100 --> 00:27:19,460
So for an economist,

530
00:27:19,460 --> 00:27:23,440
what it does is it announces an initial price vector.

531
00:27:24,780 --> 00:27:27,860
Now in left circles, I don't wanna use the word price

532
00:27:27,860 --> 00:27:30,100
because as soon as you talk about a price,

533
00:27:30,100 --> 00:27:32,400
somebody thinks there's a market.

534
00:27:32,400 --> 00:27:34,460
As a matter of fact, as soon as you talk about a price,

535
00:27:34,460 --> 00:27:37,400
some people don't even wanna talk to you.

